[{"id":27448,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Glucose is soluble in water because of having aldehyde functional group","Glucose remains in multiple isomeric form in its aqueous solution","Glucose is one of the monomer unit in sucrose","Glucose is an aldohexose"],"answer":0,"solution":"Glucose is soluble in water due to presence of alcohol functional group and extensive hydrogen bonding.<br />Glucose exist is open chain as well as cyclic forms in its aqueous solution.<br />Glucose having 6C atoms so it is hexose and having aldehyde functional group so it is aldose. Thus, aldohexose.<br />Glucose is monomer unit in sucrose with fructose.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27566,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/78121488-8602-40c2-845e-04733a998884-image.png\" style=\"width: 198px; height: 171px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/df36db35-f8ac-4730-9b51-6b7c4746f7f2-image.png\" style=\"width: 198px; height: 171px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2a7854da-71bf-4d53-953b-a4228a2a7bd4-image.png\" style=\"width: 208px; height: 194px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/997b603a-2286-4e8e-b920-79d7b18a2a41-image.png\" style=\"width: 208px; height: 194px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/68f55948-9bd0-4fc5-9c11-7029131f33b3-image.png\" style=\"width: 193px; height: 206px;\" /><br /><br />In the acidic medium, only basic nitrogen is protonated. The second nitrogen is less basic because the lone pair is involved in aromaticity, while <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> are more basic.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27590,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/94758c69-4da0-4eba-a4fb-8059cd09944d-image.png\" style=\"width: 361px; height: 99px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3d686191-3448-4413-bff2-4a3cc264ac4d-image.png\" style=\"width: 373px; height: 115px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4e0f0665-a7f4-4b2d-996d-0c0e6bc9515c-image.png\" style=\"width: 382px; height: 116px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/626163df-8071-4d18-a5d8-ff59bea2ce5b-image.png\" style=\"width: 360px; height: 114px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ad1a79a7-3d0f-4f54-a0ca-c27d308c9d73-image.png\" style=\"width: 816px; height: 124px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27526,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Fibrin","Albumin","Myosin","Collagen"],"answer":1,"solution":"Albumin is water soluble.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27572,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"133\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4deac244-83db-49ff-ada3-5a0e4e801ff7-image.png\" width=\"277\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"136\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50323d75-d266-4a59-af9a-fadb6f5fc75d-image.png\" width=\"297\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"139\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f0cddbb9-78bc-47a5-bb7f-941a1ccf9cf2-image.png\" width=\"297\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"138\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a8c0f1a9-54e8-431e-aae1-2f9b2bd2bdfd-image.png\" width=\"324\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Amino acids are organic compounds that contain amino and carboxyl functional groups, along with a side chain specific to each amino acid. The key elements of an amino acid are carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen, although other elements are found in the side chains of certain amino acids.</p><p><img height=\"107\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4440d9ce-363c-45a2-90c5-885afb29945a-image.png\" width=\"388\" /></p><p><img height=\"112\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0098184-3057-4d06-bfe4-6873ac0d50a3-image.png\" width=\"367\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27442,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["(A)-(IV), (B)-(III), (C)-(II), (D)-(I)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(II), (D)-(I)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(I), (D)-(II)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ISPGYMP0OL-LZHgUTBMXmd6Bhvn55PiEcoHbQV_15bI.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kU7Lu9Hck2cfM3HVlk0ML06N_4c2WvcQISJkHOwlNn8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27573,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Val - Ser - Thr","Leu - Ser - Thr","Thr - Ser - Val","Thr - Ser - Leu"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Amino acids are organic compounds that contain amino and carboxyl functional groups, along with a side chain specific to each amino acid. The key elements of an amino acid are carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen, although other elements are found in the side chains of certain amino acids.</p><p>Peptides are short chains of amino acids linked by peptide bonds</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/315a594d-d64c-4336-88d2-3b860d835981-image.png\" style=\"width: 253px; height: 481px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27602,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Lactose","Fructose","Sucrose","Maltose"],"answer":2,"solution":"Sucrose is a non-reducing sugar as it does not reduce Fehling reagent and Tollen's reagent.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":27496,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Aldopentose","Aldotetrose","Oxalic acid","Ketotetrose"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Seliwanoff&rsquo;s test is a chemical test which distinguishes between aldose and ketose sugars. If the sugar contains a ketone group, it is a ketose. If a sugar contains an aldehyde group, it is an aldose. This test relies on the principle that, when heated, ketoses are more rapidly dehydrated than aldoses. It is named after Theodor Seliwanoff, the chemist that devised the test. When added to a solution containing ketoses, a red color is formed rapidly indicating a positive test. When added to a solution containing aldoses, a slower forming light pink is observed instead.&nbsp;The acidic&nbsp;dehydration of the different aldopentoses&nbsp;gives&nbsp;furfural. This furfural&nbsp;combines with resorcinol to give cherry red product.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d007d354-75e8-4037-833f-683defd82260-image.png\" style=\"width: 325px; height: 300px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27468,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Primary","Tertiary","Secondary","Quaternary"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When an egg is boiled, the soluble globular protein, albumin present in it is converted to insoluble fibrous protein. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">During denaturation, its biological activity is lost. Boiling an egg causes denaturation of its protein resulting in loss of its quaternary, tertiary and secondary structures.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">But the primary structure (representing the sequence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">α</mi></math> amino acids) remains intact.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hence option A is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27594,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Maltose","Lactose","Glucose","Sucrose"],"answer":3,"solution":"Sucrose does not contain a free aldehydic or ketonic group hence it does not show mutarotation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27580,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bbba7d02-46b7-4edf-84b1-f0d77e247997-image.png\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 154px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/65fab04b-ee1e-4a55-bd53-e3e0de579a8b-image.png\" style=\"width: 184px; height: 135px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/91d745a7-74dd-46d7-bfb1-7ea304e0b6a5-image.png\" style=\"width: 181px; height: 161px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/553f9320-4f2e-458e-9a77-2b5e25037da7-image.png\" style=\"width: 177px; height: 121px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Adenosine is a nucleoside which is obtained by combination of adenine with ribose sugar.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf873100-25bb-4599-9313-12386b86bb3b-image.png\" style=\"width: 309px; height: 278px;\" /><br />Above is the structure of adenosine.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27551,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27600,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["8 molecules of ATP","6 molecules of&nbsp;ATP","18 molecules of&nbsp;ATP","10 molecules of&nbsp;ATP"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Synthesis of&nbsp;glucose molecule in photosynthesis involves following reaction:</p><p><math> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>O</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>&#160;NADP&#160; + 18 ADP&#160;</mtext> <mover accent=\"true\"> <mo>&#10230;</mo> <mtext>Light reaction</mtext> </mover> <mn>6</mn> <msub> <mtext>O</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>8</mn> <mtext>&#160;ATP</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>&#160;NADPH</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mn>6</mn> <msub> <mtext>CO</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>&#160;NADPH</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>8</mn> <mtext>&#160;ATP</mtext> <mover accent=\"true\"> <mo>&#10230;</mo> <mtext>Dark reaction</mtext> </mover> <msub> <mtext>C</mtext> <mn>6</mn> </msub> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msub> <msub> <mtext>O</mtext> <mn>6</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>&#160;NADP</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mn>8</mn> <mtext>&#160;ADP</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mn>6</mn> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>O</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mn>6</mn> <msub> <mtext>CO</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <mn>6</mn> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>O</mtext> <mo>&#10230;</mo> <msub> <mtext>C</mtext> <mn>6</mn> </msub> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msub> <msub> <mtext>O</mtext> <mn>6</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <mn>6</mn> <msub> <mtext>O</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27568,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["$(\\mathrm{A}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{Q}, \\mathrm{R}) ;(\\mathrm{B}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{S}) ;(\\mathrm{C}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{P})$","$(\\mathrm{A}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{R}) ;(\\mathrm{B}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{Q}) ;(\\mathrm{C}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{P})$","$(\\mathrm{A}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{R}) ;(\\mathrm{B}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{S}) ;(\\mathrm{C}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{Q})$","$(\\mathrm{A}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{Q}) ;(\\mathrm{B}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{S}) ;(\\mathrm{C}) \\rightarrow(\\mathrm{R})$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gc5v3xmnyFMtC6stvRoWCZV1PDPtlRow6ZdSj8ERKEw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27469,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Phosphodiester linkage","Glycosidic linkage","Disulphide linkage","Peptide linkage"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The bond joining two successive nucleotides in the same strand of DNA is called the phosphodiester bond. the phosphodiester bond is the linkage between the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>3</mn><mo>'</mo></msup></math> carbon atom of one sugar molecule and the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>5</mn><mo>'</mo></msup></math> carbon atom of another, deoxyribose in DNA and ribose in RNA.</p><p>Phosphodiester linkage</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1bb632fb-cc8c-46e1-9d7e-84c39a0b994f.png\" style=\"width: 408px; height: 470px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27531,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Fructose","Galactose","Glucose","Sucrose"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mi>Sucrose</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>Non</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>reducing</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sugar</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><munder><mi>glucose</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>Reducing</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sugar</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><munder><mi>Fructose</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>Reducing</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sugar</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27613,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{C}_5^{\\prime}$ and $\\mathrm{C}_2^{\\prime}$ respectively of the sugar molecule","$\\mathrm{C}_2^{\\prime}$ and $\\mathrm{C}_5^{\\prime}$ respectively of the sugar molecule","$\\mathrm{C}_1^{\\prime}$ and $\\mathrm{C}_5^{\\prime}$ respectively of the sugar molecule","$\\mathrm{C}_5^{\\prime}$ and $\\mathrm{C}_1^{\\prime}$ respectively of the sugar molecule"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VWSRCilgN7liRIbsaKY6G7ZSoU4Cdu2tzEb96PJlrL0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":27595,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Quinoline","Adenine","Cytosine","Thymine"],"answer":0,"solution":"DNA contains Adenine, Thymine, cytosine and Guanine.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27615,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Uracil","Thymine","Guanine","Cytosine"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27461,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Fat-soluble vitamins are stored in the body's liver, fatty tissue, and muscles. The  fat-soluble vitamins are vitamins <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo> </mo></math>. These vitamins are absorbed more easily by the body in the presence of dietary fat. Water-soluble vitamins are not stored in the body. The only <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> vitamin which is folound in liver is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>12</mn></msub></math>.</p><p>Vitamins <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>12</mn></msub></math> are stored in liver and adipose tissue.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27517,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Seliwanoff&#39;s test","Biuret test for peptide bond","Barfoed&#39;s&nbsp;test","Benedict&#39;s test"],"answer":0,"solution":"Seliwanoff&#39;s Test : This test is used to detect the presence of Ketohexose.<br />Reagent : Resorcinol <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math> conc. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>.<br />Barfoed&#39;s Test : It is&nbsp;used to detect Monosaccharide by reduction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>)</mo></math> into Copper (I). Fehling Solution: It is used to detect aldehyde by reduction <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>)</mo></math> into <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>)</mo></math>. Biuret&nbsp;Test : Use to detect presence of peptide bond in protein by reduction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>)</mo></math> into <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27486,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FIQY</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FLDY</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>YQLF</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PLDY</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8e0f9034-0a0b-499f-93b9-c87421cf20d6-5b221d5f-a997-41dc-b37b-a0a100bcf37b-9895111.png\" style=\"width: 527px; height: 370px;\" /></p><p>The peptide is having N-terminal at left-hand side and C-terminal at right-hand side. During hydrolysis the bond breaks between&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>.</p><p>Hydrolysis of the given tetrapeptide will give the following:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7929ecf0-eb62-4255-be21-0a4c5a305766-9895111_2.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 262px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1f93cdbb-9587-409d-97d3-2ab61f0ec001-9895111_3.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 238px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27458,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kHSkeMNp45xGqhfcwmvTJVb5zXvHRyaxMqv5oBD_vVQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/IaX1mQJMBzJ6ayoGvX_VX8rLqy-Bfmk1apECtIcjqGk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/K4udPZGMplnZ2Mfq642Q2T8zpuGoTjYsjN4dNKs5Dko.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tVW1C6Y0vmtv6cB2NzBGvnyilSYPpLrRnOEBzIbBIE4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Structure of L-Glucose is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/u6OPzx7u71GeXozFsSpiUaGRlBjSxU4pOfuaXEYtrjA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27587,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["3.65","2.77","5.74","1.88"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.88</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3.65</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5.53</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>2.765</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>2.77</mn></math><br /><br />At isoelectric point of aspartic&nbsp;acid both carboxylic and amino from co-exist.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27503,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>deoxyribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo></math>deoxyribose","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo></math>ribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math>deoxyribose","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>deoxyribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo></math>ribose","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>deoxyribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math>deoxyribose"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Deoxyribo nucleic acid or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DNA</mi></math> contains <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-deoxy-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-ribose sugar unit, whereas ribo nucleic acid or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RNA</mi></math> contains <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-ribose sugar unit.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/38f247e7-e476-4d85-bd03-b7b9b9a3f3bd-image.png\" style=\"width: 216px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> deoxyribose in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DNA</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b0bf1b26-1425-4253-954e-2f053e377aa6-image.png\" style=\"width: 167px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-ribose in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RNA</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27451,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["can be oxidized to a dicarboxylic acid with \\(\\mathrm{Br}_2\\) water","will coexist in equilibrium with 2 other cyclic structure","despite the presence of - \\(\\mathrm{CHO}\\) does not give Schiff's test","has 4 asymmetric carbon atom"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nvGZVjx6D2mQrsLTUC_7rTXJxW5pBr_v1a9kiIRxBj4.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/C7bhjNX5-6fZJedFZKLBje_pxf6eVI5yJoL1ZaJ7dTY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27501,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Primary","Secondary","Tertiary","Quarternary"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Protein structures are made by condensation of amino acids forming peptide bonds. The sequence of amino acids in a protein is called its primary structure. The secondary structure is determined by the dihedral angles of the peptide bonds, the tertiary structure by the folding of protein chains in space.</p><p>Denaturation involves the breaking of many of the weak linkages, or bonds (e.g., hydrogen bonds), within a protein molecule that are responsible for the highly ordered structure of the protein in its natural (native) state.&nbsp;</p><p>During denaturation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&deg;</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&deg;</mo></math> structures are destroyed but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&deg;</mo></math> structure remains intact</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27484,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Peptide linkage is also known as peptide bond. It is an amide formed between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group by elimination of a water molecule. It is represented as<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>CO</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>NH</mi><mo>-</mo></math>.</p><p>Number of peptide linkages <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo></math>Total&nbsp;amino acids&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Now, given that short peptide on hydrolysis give seven amino acids.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27515,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Keratin","Albumin","Myosin","Collagen"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Fibrous protein are animal proteins and are not soluble in water. Their molecules are typically thread-like and long, some examples are&nbsp;myosin, collagen, keratin.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null}]